attended_ch.Description: side to which participants were instructed to attend to

Levels.left: participants were instructed to attend to the left story
Levels.right: participants were instructed to attend to the right story

orig_study.Description: original study in which the participant took part

first_bl.Description: First block that is selected from each participant. Same for all participants. Always the actual first block of the experiment

second_bl.Description: Second block that is selected from each participant. Different between participants

third_bl.Description: Third block that is selected from each participant. Different between participants

con_order.Description: order of sound presentation mode during block 2-4 in Holtze et al. (2021). O stands for a block in omnidirectional mode (both audio books were equally loud). B stands for a block presented in beamformer mode (attended audio book was louder than ignored one).

Levels.OBOB: block 2: omnidirectional, block 3: beamformer, block 4: omnidirectional, block 5: beamformer
Levels.BOBO: block 2: beamformer, block 3: omnidirectional, block 4: beamformer, block 5: omnidirectional

README:
Within this study cEEGrid data from two previous studies were pooled. 
15 participants from Jaeger et al. (2020) and 21 from Holtze et al. (2021) were included. 
Participants performed a two-competing speaker paradigm in both original studies. 
Participants were instructed to either attend to the left or right audio book. 
The paradigm consisted of six (Jaeger et al. 2020) or five (Holtze et al. 2021) 
10-minute blocks of audio book presentation. In Jaeger et al. (2020) both audio 
books were always presented equally loud. In Holtze et al. 2021, a 10-minute block could 
either be presented in the omnidirectional condition (both audio books were presented 
equally loud) or in the beamforming condition (the to-be-attended audio book 
was louder than the to-be-ignored audio book). The first 10-minute block was always 
presented in the omnidirectional condition whereas the conditions were alternated 
for the later four blocks, with one half of the participants starting with the 
omnidirectonal condition and the other half starting with the beamforming condition. 
The article (https://doi.org/10.3389/fnins.2022.869426) contains all methodological details
